summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating constructor exceptions**\\n\\nI’m considering if the initial constructor, which takes no parameters, could still throw an `IllegalArgumentException` when Ant passes 256 arguments. It seems the error is related to how the JVM test handles this scenario. I noticed a stack trace involving `Constructor.newInstance`, which was present when an assertion failed, pointing to the need for JVM coverage logging. Perhaps the native test didn’t register this failure due to unsupported dynamic access. It seems that only successful reflection gets counted, and there’s a user-code filter that excludes certain classes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing dynamic access filtering**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out how dynamic access events relate to the AntClassLoader when invoking a constructor on a test class. It's possible that events are being filtered out because the target class falls under `ant.ant.*`, which is excluded. The call site report indicates `getDeclaredConstructors` is covered, but I’m wondering if the dynamic access event for this includes the call site without filtering the target class. However, for `Constructor.newInstance`, it seems that the target constructor isn’t counted. It feels a bit convoluted!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_5n3hfBlFBdg3eqDrBkVmRX6u|fc_0a68fd46c0f7d7590169f5430e7a64819494d95435a77793ac", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/ant/ant/1.6/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json", "limit": 2000}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 16547, "output": 1912, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 52251, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777681138703, "responseId": "resp_0a68fd46c0f7d7590169f542f3d70c81948d23b87fa532283d"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_5n3hfBlFBdg3eqDrBkVmRX6